  <!--
    (E)* citation
        (A)** name: citation name, must be unique for all citations defined
        (A)** sensitive-fields-name: The citaton won't be generated if given sensitive field(s) are null or empty.
        (E)** field
            (E)*** max-n-value: designed with max-n-ending attribute for author display.
                Use Case -  if an item has more than 3 authors, and the citation will only display first 3 authors
                            and replace other authors with "et al.", you can put max-n-value="3" max-n-ending="et al."
                            attributes in the author field
            (E)*** max-n-ending: see max-n-value
            (E)*** noshow-if-exist: don't show this field if specified field(s) exists.
                Sample Value: "dc.contributor.author" or "dc.pubplace;dc.contributor.publisher" (multiple fields seperated with ";")
            (E)*** show-if-exist: show this field if specified field(s) exists.
                Sample Value: "dc.contributor.author" or "dc.pubplace;dc.contributor.publisher" (multiple fields seperated with ";")
            (E)*** op: used with noshow-if-exist or show-if-exist when there are multiple fields specified. Value set is ("AND", "OR")
            (A)*** dc-schema: you can specify any schema here, dc or whatever you name it
            (A)*** dc-element: the element name
            (A)*** dc-qualifier: the qualifier name
            (A)*** display-format: Here is the place you can format your citation.
                    @field@ will be replaced by the actural field value. Also you can apply html tags. See [Note 1]
                    for supported html tags.
                (E)**** multiple-value-seperator: Use this seperator to seperate multiple-value field. Default is ", ".
                (E)**** format-it: The attribute is used to customize the field value - @field@ itself.
                        In dspace-api/.../app/util/FormatIt.java, you will find a method formatIt. All format-it attributes are
                        handled over here. Here are the steps to format your field (for multiple-value field, it formats
                        each individual value.)
                        Step 1 - Name your format, for example "firstname-initial-only"
                        Step 2 - Write your format method in FormatIt.java, for example,
                            String getFirstNameInitials(String value)
                        Step 3 - add a line to formatIt method
                            if(formatit.equalsIgnoreCase("firstname-initial-only")){
                                    return getFirstNameInitials(value);
                            }
                        Of course, you need to compile the code, deploy, and restart the web application.

    Special use case - a field without a field value
            If you would like to put a punctuation or a phrase which is not related to any metadata field in the citation,
            you can leave the dc-schema, dc-element, and dc-qualifier empty, and put whatever you want in display-format.
            For example,

           <field show-if-exist="dc.pubplace;dc.contributor.publisher" op="AND">
             <dc-schema></dc-schema>
             <dc-element></dc-element>
             <dc-qualifier></dc-qualifier>
             <display-format>:</display-format>
           </field>


    [Note 1]
          This method is applicable to XMLUI.
          For html tag like <i> </i>, you need to escape "<" as "&lt;" and ">" as "&gt;".
          Before you send the page to the browser, you need to apply html-tag-parser.xsl to the field so that these tags
          can be interpreted as HTML. Currently, html-tag-parser.xsl supports tag <i>, <b>, <a>, and <p>. You can change
          the parser to support more tags by updating this line:
           <xsl:when test="contains($str,'&lt;i') or contains($str, '&lt;b') or contains($str, '&lt;a') or contains($str, '&lt;p')">

    *************************************************************************  -->

